{"title_page": "Frank Gibbs Torto", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{short description|Ghanaian chemist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name = Frank Gibbs Torto\n|honorific_suffix = [[Ghana Academy of Arts and Sciences|FGA]], [[Order of the Volta|OV]] \n|birth_name = Frank Gibbs Tetteh Obaka Torto\n|birth_date = {{birth date|1921|10|10}}\n|birth_place = [[Accra]], [[Gold Coast (British colony)|Gold Coast]]\n|death_date = {{death date and age|1984|5|7|1921|10|10|df=y}}\n|death_place = [[Ghana]]\n|spouse = {{marriage|Iris Aku Torto,n\u00e9e Akwei|1949|2008|reason=died}} \n|children = Oboshie Adjua Torto, Obodai Torto, Ofori Torto.\n|nationality = Ghanaian\n|ethnicity =\n|field = Chemistry\n|work_institutions = [[University of Ghana]]\n|alma_mater = [[University of London]]\n|known_for =\n|religion =\n|footnotes =\n|signature =\n}}\n\n'''Frank Gibbs Tetteh Obaka Torto''', [[Ghana Academy of Arts and Sciences|FGA]], [[Order of the Volta|OV]] (10 October 1921 \u2013 May  1984) was a [[Ghanaian]] [[chemist]] and a [[professor]] at the [[University of Ghana]]. He was a founding member, vice president and later president of the [[Ghana Academy of Arts and Sciences]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nFrank was born on 10 October 1921 in [[Accra]].\n\nHe was educated in many elementary schools in the [[Gold Coast (British colony)|Gold Coast]]. In 1931, he enrolled at the [[Accra Academy]] as one of the school's foundation students.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mensah |first=J. N. A. |date=2013 |title=Traditions and customs of Gadangmes of Ghana : descendants of authentic Biblical Hebrew Israelites |url=https://books.google.com/?id=8tYeAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA277&dq=torto+accra+academy#v=onepage&q=torto%20accra%20academy&f=false |page=277|isbn=9781628571042 }}</ref> He completed in 1936 and joined the intermediate department of [[Achimota School|Achimota College]] a year later to pursue an intermediate bachelor's degree which he received in 1941. In 1942, he proceeded to the [[United Kingdom]] for his tertiary education. He was accepted into the [[Queen Mary University of London]] a constituent college of the [[University of London]] studying there from the bachelors level; graduating with first class honours<ref>{{cite journal |title=Proceedings of the Ghana Academy of Sciences. |publisher=Secretariat of the Ghana Academy of Sciences, 1964-1968 |page=17 |date=1963}}</ref> to doctorate level, he was awarded his doctorate (Ph. D.) degree in Chemistry in 1947.<ref name=\"OBAKA\">{{cite book |last=Uwechue |first=Ralph |title=Africa Who's who |url=https://books.google.com/?id=9EAOAQAAMAAJ&q=frank+gibbs+tetteh+obaka+torto&dq=frank+gibbs+tetteh+obaka+torto |publisher=Africa Journal Limited |page=1735 |date=1991|isbn=9780903274173 }}</ref><ref name= \"TETTEH\">{{cite book |title=International book of honor |url=https://books.google.com/?id=d8_F3KRx3iIC&q=frank+gibbs+torto&dq=frank+gibbs+torto |publisher=American Biographical Institute |page=373 |date=1987|isbn = 9780934544320}}</ref><ref name= \"FRANK\">{{cite journal |title=Ghana Year Book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=njAuAQAAIAAJ&q=frank+gibbs+torto&dq=frank+gibbs+torto |publisher=Graphic Corporation |page=286 |date=1978}}</ref><ref name=\"F G T O TORTO\">{{cite book |title=Who's who in the world |url=https://books.google.com/?id=3foKAQAAMAAJ&dq=ernest+amano+boateng&q=Torto |publisher=Wilmette, Ill. : Marquis Who's Who, Macmillan Directory Division |page=696 |date=1978|isbn = 9780837911038}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHe returned to Ghana in 1947 after his studies abroad and joined the faculty of Achimota College's intermediate department as a lecturer. A year later when the University College of the Gold Coast was founded he together with [[Walter Warwick Sawyer]], D. K. Baldwin and Mary C. Charnley all from the Intermediate department were appointed as the first group of staff to form the nucleus of the university's teaching faculty<ref>{{cite book |last=Agbodeka |first=Francis |date=1998 |title=A history of University of Ghana:\u00a0half a century of higher education (1948-1998) |url=https://books.google.com/?id=l9wsAQAAIAAJ&q=torto+chemistry+first&dq=torto+chemistry+first |page=45|isbn=9789964978563 }}</ref> thereby making him the first Ghanaian lecturer of the university.<ref>{{cite book |last=Agbodeka |first=Francis |date=1998 |title=A history of University of Ghana:\u00a0half a century of higher education (1948-1998) |url=https://books.google.com/?id=l9wsAQAAIAAJ&dq=torto+chemistry+first&q=+member+consider+whole |page=217|isbn=9789964978563 }}</ref> He was a lecturer of chemistry at the university in 1948 and a senior lecturer in 1957. He became a Ghana [[UNESCO]] National Commission member in 1958 and in 1959 became a founding member of the [[Ghana Academy of Arts and Sciences]]. A year later, he was appointed a scientific consultant for the [[United Nations]]. In 1962 he rose to professorship status and the head of the chemistry department.<ref>{{cite book |last=Addy |first=M. A. |authorlink=Marian Ewurama Addy |date=2011 |title=Rewards : an autobiography |url=https://books.google.com/?id=9gpkHOFb5DwC&pg=PA320&dq=daniel+adzei+bekoe#v=onepage&q=Torto&f=false |page=48|isbn=9789988037826 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Feeding Africa:\u00a0Proceedings of the Second Symposium of Pan African Pugwash Group, 28th May - 3rd June 1978, Cape Coast University, Ghana |url=https://books.google.com/?id=lEwCAAAAMAAJ&q=f+g+torto&dq=f+g+torto |publisher=Pan African Pugwash Group |page=18 |date=1978}}</ref> That same year, he was named with [[Stephen Oluwole Awokoya]] by the then [[Secretary-General of the United Nations]]; [[U Thant]] among eight scientific secretaries for a United Nations conference on the application of science and technology for the benefit of less developed areas, a conference that was held in [[Geneva]], [[Switzerland]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=West Africa, Issues \u00a02328-2352 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=EBkOAQAAMAAJ&q=f+g+torto&dq=f+g+torto |publisher=Afrimedia International |page=194 |date=1962}}</ref> In 1965, he was appointed president of the Ghana Science Association and a year later, president of the Association of Science Teachers.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Ghana Year Book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=KDAuAQAAIAAJ&q=f+g+torto&dq=f+g+torto |publisher=Graphic Corporation |page=275 |date=1967}}</ref> In October, 1968 he was a visiting fellow at [[Churchill College]], [[University of Cambridge]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=Cambridge University Reporter, Volume 98, Issue 3 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=S9cDI8t2d4sC&dq=f+g+torto+award&q=f+g+torto |publisher=University of Cambridge |page=2562 |date=1968}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Register |url=https://books.google.com/?id=n32NIwBTM6IC&q=frank+gibbs+torto&dq=frank+gibbs+torto |publisher=Cambridge Auxiliary Fire Department |page=640 |date=1970}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=The Cambridge University List of Members for the Year |url=https://books.google.com/?id=05AcAQAAMAAJ&dq=frank+gibbs+torto&q=Torto |publisher=Cambridge Auxiliary Fire Department |page=1366 |date=1991}}</ref> He was then appointed dean of the faculty of Science at the University of Ghana in 1969 taking over from [[Alan Nunn May]], he served in this capacity until 1971.<ref>{{cite book |last=Daniel |first=Ebow |date=1999 |title=Mr. Registrar : the making of an amanuensis |url=https://books.google.com/?id=JOwsAQAAIAAJ&q=f+g+torto&dq=f+g+torto |page=120|isbn=9789964978594 }}</ref> In 1972 he became a member of the continuing committee of the [[Pugwash Conferences on Science and World Affairs]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=Proceedings of the Twenty-fifth Pugwash Conference on Science and World Affairs:\u00a0Development, Resources and World Security, Madras, India, 13-19 January, 1976 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=-w0KAQAAIAAJ&q=frank+torto&dq=frank+torto |publisher=Pugwash Conference on Science and World Affairs |page=62 |date=1976}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Rotblat |first=Joseph |authorlink=Joseph Rotblat |date=1972 |title=Crisis, Change, and Revolution in Ghanaian Education |url=https://books.google.com/?id=BbLaAAAAMAAJ&q=frank+torto&dq=frank+torto |page=89|isbn=9780262180542 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Pugwash Newsletter, Volume 24-25 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=l58kAQAAIAAJ&q=f+g+torto&dq=f+g+torto |publisher=Council of the Pugwash Conferences on Science and World Affairs |page=ii |date=1974}}</ref> In 1973 he was made dean of the faculty of science for a second occasion.<ref>{{cite book |author=Unesco. Regional Office of Science and Technology for Africa. |date=1975 |title=Final Report |url=https://books.google.com/?id=UcaIrqgE-LUC&q=f+g+torto&dq=f+g+torto}}</ref> This time he served in that capacity for a year. In 1978 he served on the [[United Nations]] advisory committee.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Oficial Records, Volume 1 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=5_5o8vdvAwYC&q=f+g+torto&dq=f+g+torto |publisher=United Nations. Economic and Social Council |page=243 |date=1978}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Stuart |first=Sam |date=2016 |title=Science, Technology and Global Problems: The United Nations Advisory |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Zel3DAAAQBAJ&pg=PA60&dq=f+g+torto+london#v=onepage&q=f%20g%20torto%20london&f=false |page=60|isbn=9781483189451 }}</ref> In 1979 he served on the board of Ghana National Manganese Corporation. That same year, he was appointed vice president of the Ghana Academy of Arts and Sciences. He served in this capacity until 1981 when he was appointed president of the academic body.\nIn his lifetime, Frank served on various other committees and organizations some of which include; the [[Council for Scientific and Industrial Research \u2013 Ghana]] and the Council of the Centre for Scientific Research into Plant Medicine. He was also an editorial board member for the West African Journal of Biological and Applied Chemistry.<ref>{{cite journal |title=West African Journal of Biological and Applied Chemistry, Volumes 6-11 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=xsRFAAAAYAAJ&q=f+g+torto&dq=f+g+torto |publisher=J. M. P. Services |page=71 |date=1962}}</ref><ref name=\"OBAKA\"/><ref name=\"TETTEH\"/><ref name=\"FRANK\"/><ref name=\"F G T O TORTO\"/> He also served as an external examiner for the West African Examinations Council for years, in addition to serving as a member of the board of directors for Adisadel College, Cape Coast.\n\n==Honours and legacies==\nHe was a recipient of the member of the\u00a0[[Order of the Volta]]\u00a0award.<ref name= \"TETTEH\"/>\n\nThe University of Ghana award for best graduating student in chemistry is named after him.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ug.edu.gh/academic-prize-awards-20132014 |title=Academic Prize Awards \u2013 2013/2014 |publisher=UNIVERSITY OF GHANA |accessdate=12 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe University of Ghana Chemistry building was also named in his honour.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Annual Report |url=https://books.google.com/?id=L6clAQAAIAAJ&q=frank+torto&dq=frank+torto |publisher=State Publishing Company |page=xxxviii |date=2007}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\nFrank authored many articles that were published in scientific and general publications. His works have been featured in journals such as; the [[Journal of the Chemical Society]], [[Nature (journal)]], West African Journal of Biological Science and the Ghana Journal of Science.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Ghana Journal of Science:\u00a0A Joint Publication of the Council for Scientific and Industrial Research and the Ghana Science Association, Volumes 7-12 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=7jG5AAAAIAAJ&q=f+g+torto&dq=f+g+torto |publisher=Council for Scientific and Industrial Research (Ghana) |page=3 |date=1967}}</ref> Some of his works include;\n\n*(contrib.) ''Some Problems in the Study of Plant Gum Polyssacharides'', 1960;<ref>{{cite journal |title=West African Journal of Biological Chemistry, Volumes 4-5 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=UYIIAQAAIAAJ&q=f+g+torto&dq=fto |publisher=University College |page=6 |date=1960}}</ref>\n*(contrib.) ''An Aldobiouronic Acid Isolated from Fagara xanthoxyloides Gum'', 1961;<ref>{{cite journal |title=Journal of the Chemical Society |url=https://books.google.com/?id=yKpm4Ld4oQoC&q=f+g+torto&dq=f+g+torto |publisher=Chemical Society |page=3166 |date=1961}}</ref>\n*(contrib.) ''The training of scientists in Ghana\" in scientific world'', 1964;<ref>{{cite journal |title=scientific world vol VIII, No. 4 |pages=3\u20138 |date=1964}}</ref>\n*(contrib.) ''Arms and African Development'' Ed. F S Arkhurst: Praeger, 1972;<ref name=\"OBAKA\"/>\n*(contrib.) ''Views of Science Technology and Development'' Ed. V. Rabinowitch: Pergamon, 1975;<ref name=\"OBAKA\"/>\n* ''Structure of the Alkaloid Wisanine (2-Methoxypiperine)'', 1981;<ref name= \"TETTEH\"/>\n* ''University Chemistry in Developing Countries'', 1981;<ref name= \"TETTEH\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nFrank married Iris Aku Torto (''n\u00e9e'' Akwei) in 1949. Together they had three children; Oboshie Adjua Torto, Obodai Torto and Ofori Torto. He enjoyed listening to music in his spare time, and played classical piano.<ref name=\"OBAKA\"/><ref name= \"TETTEH\"/><ref name= \"FRANK\"/> He died in May, 1984.<ref>{{cite journal |title=roceedings of the Pugwash Conference on Science and World Affairs., Volume 35 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=-qEkAQAAIAAJ&q=frank+torto&dq=frank+torto |publisher=Pugwash Conference on Science and World Affairs |page=45 |date=1985}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Pugwash Newsletter, Volume 22 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ZD9DAQAAIAAJ&q=frank+torto&dq=frank+torto |publisher=Council of the Pugwash Conferences on Science and World Affairs |page=111 |date=1985}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ghana Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Torto, Frank Gibbs}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:1984 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century chemists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Ghanaian educators]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Accra Academy]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Achimota School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Queen Mary University of London]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Churchill College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Ga-Adangbe people]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian chemists]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian Protestants]]\n[[Category:People from Accra]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Volta]]\n[[Category:University of Ghana faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{short description|Ghanaian chemist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name = Frank Gibbs Torto\n|honorific_suffix = [[Ghana Academy of Arts and Sciences|FGA]], [[Order of the Volta|OV]] \n|birth_name = Frank Gibbs Tetteh Obaka Torto\n|birth_date = {{birth date|1921|10|10}}\n|birth_place = [[Accra]], [[Gold Coast (British colony)|Gold Coast]]\n|death_date = {{death date and age|1984|5|7|1921|10|10|df=y}}\n|death_place = [[Ghana]]\n|spouse = {{marriage|Iris Aku Torto,n\u00e9e Akwei|1949|2008|reason=died}} \n|children = Oboshie Adjua Torto, Obodai Torto, Ofori Torto.\n|nationality = Ghanaian\n|ethnicity =\n|field = Chemistry\n|work_institutions = [[University of Ghana]]\n|alma_mater = [[University of London]]\n|known_for =\n|religion =\n|footnotes =\n|signature =\n}}\n\n'''Frank Gibbs Tetteh Obaka Torto''', [[Ghana Academy of Arts and Sciences|FGA]], [[Order of the Volta|OV]] (10 October 1921 \u2013 May  1984) was a [[Ghanaian]] [[chemist]] and a [[professor]] at the [[University of Ghana]]. He was a founding member, vice president and later president of the [[Ghana Academy of Arts and Sciences]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nFrank was born on 10 October 1921 in [[Accra]].\n\nHe was educated in many elementary schools in the [[Gold Coast (British colony)|Gold Coast]]. In 1931, he enrolled at the [[Accra Academy]] as one of the school's foundation students.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mensah |first=J. N. A. |date=2013 |title=Traditions and customs of Gadangmes of Ghana : descendants of authentic Biblical Hebrew Israelites |url=https://books.google.com/?id=8tYeAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA277&dq=torto+accra+academy#v=onepage&q=torto%20accra%20academy&f=false |page=277|isbn=9781628571042 }}</ref> He completed in 1936 and joined the intermediate department of [[Achimota School|Achimota College]] a year later to pursue an intermediate bachelor's degree which he received in 1941. In 1942, he proceeded to the [[United Kingdom]] for his tertiary education. He was accepted into the [[Queen Mary University of London]] a constituent college of the [[University of London]] studying there from the bachelors level; graduating with first class honours<ref>{{cite journal |title=Proceedings of the Ghana Academy of Sciences. |publisher=Secretariat of the Ghana Academy of Sciences, 1964-1968 |page=17 |date=1963}}</ref> to doctorate level, he was awarded his doctorate (Ph. D.) degree in Chemistry in 1947.<ref name=\"OBAKA\">{{cite book |last=Uwechue |first=Ralph |title=Africa Who's who |url=https://books.google.com/?id=9EAOAQAAMAAJ&q=frank+gibbs+tetteh+obaka+torto&dq=frank+gibbs+tetteh+obaka+torto |publisher=Africa Journal Limited |page=1735 |date=1991|isbn=9780903274173 }}</ref><ref name= \"TETTEH\">{{cite book |title=International book of honor |url=https://books.google.com/?id=d8_F3KRx3iIC&q=frank+gibbs+torto&dq=frank+gibbs+torto |publisher=American Biographical Institute |page=373 |date=1987|isbn = 9780934544320}}</ref><ref name= \"FRANK\">{{cite journal |title=Ghana Year Book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=njAuAQAAIAAJ&q=frank+gibbs+torto&dq=frank+gibbs+torto |publisher=Graphic Corporation |page=286 |date=1978}}</ref><ref name=\"F G T O TORTO\">{{cite book |title=Who's who in the world |url=https://books.google.com/?id=3foKAQAAMAAJ&dq=ernest+amano+boateng&q=Torto |publisher=Wilmette, Ill. : Marquis Who's Who, Macmillan Directory Division |page=696 |date=1978|isbn = 9780837911038}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHe returned to Ghana in 1947 after his studies abroad and joined the faculty of Achimota College's intermediate department as a lecturer. A year later when the University College of the Gold Coast was founded he together with [[Walter Warwick Sawyer]], D. K. Baldwin and Mary C. Charnley all from the Intermediate department were appointed as the first group of staff to form the nucleus of the university's teaching faculty<ref>{{cite book |last=Agbodeka |first=Francis |date=1998 |title=A history of University of Ghana:\u00a0half a century of higher education (1948-1998) |url=https://books.google.com/?id=l9wsAQAAIAAJ&q=torto+chemistry+first&dq=torto+chemistry+first |page=45|isbn=9789964978563 }}</ref> thereby making him the first Ghanaian lecturer of the university.<ref>{{cite book |last=Agbodeka |first=Francis |date=1998 |title=A history of University of Ghana:\u00a0half a century of higher education (1948-1998) |url=https://books.google.com/?id=l9wsAQAAIAAJ&dq=torto+chemistry+first&q=+member+consider+whole |page=217|isbn=9789964978563 }}</ref> He was a lecturer of chemistry at the university in 1948 and a senior lecturer in 1957. He became a Ghana [[UNESCO]] National Commission member in 1958 and in 1959 became a founding member of the [[Ghana Academy of Arts and Sciences]]. A year later, he was appointed a scientific consultant for the [[United Nations]]. In 1962 he rose to professorship status and the head of the chemistry department.<ref>{{cite book |last=Addy |first=M. A. |authorlink=Marian Ewurama Addy |date=2011 |title=Rewards : an autobiography |url=https://books.google.com/?id=9gpkHOFb5DwC&pg=PA320&dq=daniel+adzei+bekoe#v=onepage&q=Torto&f=false |page=48|isbn=9789988037826 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Feeding Africa:\u00a0Proceedings of the Second Symposium of Pan African Pugwash Group, 28th May - 3rd June 1978, Cape Coast University, Ghana |url=https://books.google.com/?id=lEwCAAAAMAAJ&q=f+g+torto&dq=f+g+torto |publisher=Pan African Pugwash Group |page=18 |date=1978}}</ref> That same year, he was named with [[Stephen Oluwole Awokoya]] by the then [[Secretary-General of the United Nations]]; [[U Thant]] among eight scientific secretaries for a United Nations conference on the application of science and technology for the benefit of less developed areas, a conference that was held in [[Geneva]], [[Switzerland]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=West Africa, Issues \u00a02328-2352 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=EBkOAQAAMAAJ&q=f+g+torto&dq=f+g+torto |publisher=Afrimedia International |page=194 |date=1962}}</ref> In 1965, he was appointed president of the Ghana Science Association and a year later, president of the Association of Science Teachers.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Ghana Year Book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=KDAuAQAAIAAJ&q=f+g+torto&dq=f+g+torto |publisher=Graphic Corporation |page=275 |date=1967}}</ref> In October, 1968 he was a visiting fellow at [[Churchill College]], [[University of Cambridge]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=Cambridge University Reporter, Volume 98, Issue 3 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=S9cDI8t2d4sC&dq=f+g+torto+award&q=f+g+torto |publisher=University of Cambridge |page=2562 |date=1968}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Register |url=https://books.google.com/?id=n32NIwBTM6IC&q=frank+gibbs+torto&dq=frank+gibbs+torto |publisher=Cambridge Auxiliary Fire Department |page=640 |date=1970}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=The Cambridge University List of Members for the Year |url=https://books.google.com/?id=05AcAQAAMAAJ&dq=frank+gibbs+torto&q=Torto |publisher=Cambridge Auxiliary Fire Department |page=1366 |date=1991}}</ref> He was then appointed dean of the faculty of Science at the University of Ghana in 1969 taking over from [[Alan Nunn May]], he served in this capacity until 1971.<ref>{{cite book |last=Daniel |first=Ebow |date=1999 |title=Mr. Registrar : the making of an amanuensis |url=https://books.google.com/?id=JOwsAQAAIAAJ&q=f+g+torto&dq=f+g+torto |page=120|isbn=9789964978594 }}</ref> In 1972 he became a member of the continuing committee of the [[Pugwash Conferences on Science and World Affairs]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=Proceedings of the Twenty-fifth Pugwash Conference on Science and World Affairs:\u00a0Development, Resources and World Security, Madras, India, 13-19 January, 1976 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=-w0KAQAAIAAJ&q=frank+torto&dq=frank+torto |publisher=Pugwash Conference on Science and World Affairs |page=62 |date=1976}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Rotblat |first=Joseph |authorlink=Joseph Rotblat |date=1972 |title=Crisis, Change, and Revolution in Ghanaian Education |url=https://books.google.com/?id=BbLaAAAAMAAJ&q=frank+torto&dq=frank+torto |page=89|isbn=9780262180542 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Pugwash Newsletter, Volume 24-25 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=l58kAQAAIAAJ&q=f+g+torto&dq=f+g+torto |publisher=Council of the Pugwash Conferences on Science and World Affairs |page=ii |date=1974}}</ref> In 1973 he was made dean of the faculty of science for a second occasion.<ref>{{cite book |author=Unesco. Regional Office of Science and Technology for Africa. |date=1975 |title=Final Report |url=https://books.google.com/?id=UcaIrqgE-LUC&q=f+g+torto&dq=f+g+torto}}</ref> This time he served in that capacity for a year. In 1978 he served on the [[United Nations]] advisory committee.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Oficial Records, Volume 1 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=5_5o8vdvAwYC&q=f+g+torto&dq=f+g+torto |publisher=United Nations. Economic and Social Council |page=243 |date=1978}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Stuart |first=Sam |date=2016 |title=Science, Technology and Global Problems: The United Nations Advisory |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Zel3DAAAQBAJ&pg=PA60&dq=f+g+torto+london#v=onepage&q=f%20g%20torto%20london&f=false |page=60|isbn=9781483189451 }}</ref> In 1979 he served on the board of Ghana National Manganese Corporation. That same year, he was appointed vice president of the Ghana Academy of Arts and Sciences. He served in this capacity until 1981 when he was appointed president of the academic body.\nIn his lifetime, Frank served on various other committees and organizations some of which include; the [[Council for Scientific and Industrial Research \u2013 Ghana]] and the Council of the Centre for Scientific Research into Plant Medicine. He was also an editorial board member for the West African Journal of Biological and Applied Chemistry.<ref>{{cite journal |title=West African Journal of Biological and Applied Chemistry, Volumes 6-11 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=xsRFAAAAYAAJ&q=f+g+torto&dq=f+g+torto |publisher=J. M. P. Services |page=71 |date=1962}}</ref><ref name=\"OBAKA\"/><ref name=\"TETTEH\"/><ref name=\"FRANK\"/><ref name=\"F G T O TORTO\"/>He also served as an external examiner for the West African Examinations Council for years, in addition to serving as a member of the board of directors for Adisadel College, Cape Coast.\n\n==Honours and legacies==\nHe was a recipient of the member of the\u00a0[[Order of the Volta]]\u00a0award.<ref name= \"TETTEH\"/>\n\nThe University of Ghana award for best graduating student in chemistry is named after him.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ug.edu.gh/academic-prize-awards-20132014 |title=Academic Prize Awards \u2013 2013/2014 |publisher=UNIVERSITY OF GHANA |accessdate=12 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe University of Ghana Chemistry building was also named in his honour.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Annual Report |url=https://books.google.com/?id=L6clAQAAIAAJ&q=frank+torto&dq=frank+torto |publisher=State Publishing Company |page=xxxviii |date=2007}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\nFrank authored many articles that were published in scientific and general publications. His works have been featured in journals such as; the [[Journal of the Chemical Society]], [[Nature (journal)]], West African Journal of Biological Science and the Ghana Journal of Science.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Ghana Journal of Science:\u00a0A Joint Publication of the Council for Scientific and Industrial Research and the Ghana Science Association, Volumes 7-12 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=7jG5AAAAIAAJ&q=f+g+torto&dq=f+g+torto |publisher=Council for Scientific and Industrial Research (Ghana) |page=3 |date=1967}}</ref> Some of his works include;\n\n*(contrib.) ''Some Problems in the Study of Plant Gum Polyssacharides'', 1960;<ref>{{cite journal |title=West African Journal of Biological Chemistry, Volumes 4-5 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=UYIIAQAAIAAJ&q=f+g+torto&dq=fto |publisher=University College |page=6 |date=1960}}</ref>\n*(contrib.) ''An Aldobiouronic Acid Isolated from Fagara xanthoxyloides Gum'', 1961;<ref>{{cite journal |title=Journal of the Chemical Society |url=https://books.google.com/?id=yKpm4Ld4oQoC&q=f+g+torto&dq=f+g+torto |publisher=Chemical Society |page=3166 |date=1961}}</ref>\n*(contrib.) ''The training of scientists in Ghana\" in scientific world'', 1964;<ref>{{cite journal |title=scientific world vol VIII, No. 4 |pages=3\u20138 |date=1964}}</ref>\n*(contrib.) ''Arms and African Development'' Ed. F S Arkhurst: Praeger, 1972;<ref name=\"OBAKA\"/>\n*(contrib.) ''Views of Science Technology and Development'' Ed. V. Rabinowitch: Pergamon, 1975;<ref name=\"OBAKA\"/>\n* ''Structure of the Alkaloid Wisanine (2-Methoxypiperine)'', 1981;<ref name= \"TETTEH\"/>\n* ''University Chemistry in Developing Countries'', 1981;<ref name= \"TETTEH\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nFrank married Iris Aku Torto (''n\u00e9e'' Akwei) in 1949. Together they had three children; Oboshie Adjua Torto, Obodai Torto and Ofori Torto. He enjoyed listening to music in his spare time, and played classical piano.<ref name=\"OBAKA\"/><ref name= \"TETTEH\"/><ref name= \"FRANK\"/> He died in May, 1984.<ref>{{cite journal |title=roceedings of the Pugwash Conference on Science and World Affairs., Volume 35 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=-qEkAQAAIAAJ&q=frank+torto&dq=frank+torto |publisher=Pugwash Conference on Science and World Affairs |page=45 |date=1985}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Pugwash Newsletter, Volume 22 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ZD9DAQAAIAAJ&q=frank+torto&dq=frank+torto |publisher=Council of the Pugwash Conferences on Science and World Affairs |page=111 |date=1985}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ghana Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Torto, Frank Gibbs}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:1984 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century chemists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Ghanaian educators]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Accra Academy]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Achimota School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Queen Mary University of London]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Churchill College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Ga-Adangbe people]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian chemists]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian Protestants]]\n[[Category:People from Accra]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Volta]]\n[[Category:University of Ghana faculty]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank_Gibbs_Torto"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Saskatchewan", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Saskatchewan}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Saskatchewan\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Saskatchewan]], [[Canada]]\n| first_outbreak  = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| index_case      = [[Saskatoon]]\n| arrival_date    = March 9, 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=9|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| confirmed_cases = 341 (Includes 1 presumptive case)\n| active_cases    = 57\n| recovery_cases  = 280\n| deaths          = 4\n| website         = {{URL|https://www.saskatchewan.ca/COVID19}}\n| map1            = Saskatchewan COVID-19 Infection Rates.svg\n| map1_size       = 200px\n| map1_upright    = 1\n| alt1            = Map of COVID-19 infection density by region.\n| legend1         = Total cases by region, per 100,000 residents (2018 population estimate):\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}{{legend|#900000|>48}}{{legend|#c80200|>36}}\n{{col-break}}{{legend|#ee7070|>24}}{{legend|#ffc0c0|>12}}\n{{col-break}}{{legend|#ffdfe0|>0}}{{legend|#e0e0e0|0}}\n{{col-end}}\n}}\n\nThe '''2020 coronavirus pandemic in Saskatchewan''' is an [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ongoing viral pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), a novel infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2). {{As of|2020|04|23|df=US}}, 25,872 tests have been conducted, with 330 confirmed cases, one presumptive case, 270 recoveries, and 4 deaths in Saskatchewan.<ref name=\"saskcovid19\">{{cite web |url=https://www.saskatchewan.ca/government/health-care-administration-and-provider-resources/treatment-procedures-and-guidelines/emerging-public-health-issues/2019-novel-coronavirus/cases-and-risk-of-covid-19-in-saskatchewan |title=Cases and Risk of COVID-19 in Saskatchewan (updated daily) |website=Government of Saskatchewan}}</ref> The areas of the former [[Saskatoon Health Region]], [[Regina Qu'Appelle Health Region]], and a composite of the [[Prairie North Health Region|Prairie North]], Prince Albert Parkland, and Kelsey Trail Health Regions, have seen the majority of Saskatchewan's cases.\n\nA provincial state of emergency was declared on March 18, and the province began to institute mandatory closures of non-essential facilities and lines of business over the days that followed. By early-April, the number of new cases within Saskatchewan began to trend downwards; on April 6, the number of new recoveries began to regularly equal or exceed the number of new cases, which also began to steadily drop. On April 23, the province unveiled a plan to gradually begin lifting economic restrictions on May 4, although restrictions on larger public gatherings, school closures, and self-isolation following travel will remain in force for the foreseeable future.\n\n==Timeline==\nSaskatchewan's Chief Medical Officer Saqib Shahab announced the first presumptive case of in the province on March 12, a person in their 60s that had recently returned from [[Egypt]], who was tested on March 9, and was in self-isolation at their home.<ref name=\"first\">{{cite news |last1=Giles |first1=David |title=Saskatchewan confirms first presumptive case of novel coronavirus |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6666466/coronavirus-saskatchewan-covid-19-coronavirus-saskatoon/ |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=Global News |publisher=Corus Entertainment |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> By March 16, the number of presumptive cases in the province had increased to seven.<ref name=\"cases316\">{{cite news |last1=Giles |first1=David |title=Saskatchewan reports 7th presumptive case of coronavirus |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6685561/confirmed-presumptive-cases-covid-19-saskatchewan-coronavirus/ |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=Global News |publisher=Corus Entertainment |date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317145935/https://globalnews.ca/news/6685561/confirmed-presumptive-cases-covid-19-saskatchewan-coronavirus/ |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 17, one new case was reported.<ref name=\"case317\">{{cite news |last1=Davis |first1=Austin |title=COVID-19: Sask. records eighth case of coronavirus |url=https://leaderpost.com/news/saskatchewan/covid-19-live-updates-03-17/ |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=Regina Leader-Post |publisher=Postmedia |date=March 17, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319184303/https://leaderpost.com/news/saskatchewan/covid-19-live-updates-03-17/ |archive-date=March 19, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On the same day, the College of Dental Surgeons of Saskatchewan recommended that those who attended the 2020 Pacific Dental Conference in [[Vancouver]] to self-isolate after many cases, including two in Saskatchewan, were linked to the event.<ref name=\"dentistemergency\">{{cite news |last1=Warick |first1=Jason |title=Sask. dentists asked to consider limiting work to emergencies only |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/dentists-asked-emergency-work-only-1.5501058 |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=CBC News |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |date=March 17, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319123046/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/dentists-asked-emergency-work-only-1.5501058 |archive-date=March 19, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 18, 8 new cases were reported.<ref name=\"emergency\">{{cite news |last1=Davis |first1=Austin |title=Sask. declares state of emergency after eight new coronavirus cases |url=https://leaderpost.com/news/saskatchewan/covid-19-live-updates-03-18/ |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=Regina Leader-Post |publisher=Postmedia |date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319183516/https://leaderpost.com/news/saskatchewan/covid-19-live-updates-03-18/ |archive-date=March 19, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 19, four new cases were reported, bringing the provincial total to 20.<ref name=\"cases319\">{{cite news |last1=Davis |first1=Austin |title=COVID-19: Sask. reports four new coronavirus cases, bringing total to 20 |url=https://leaderpost.com/news/saskatchewan/covid-19-live-updates-03-19/ |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=Regina Leader-Post |publisher=Postmedia |date=March 19, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320164217/https://leaderpost.com/news/saskatchewan/covid-19-live-updates-03-19/ |archive-date=March 20, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 20, six new cases were reported, and 8 were confirmed.<ref name=\"cases320\">{{cite news |last1=Guignard |first1=Jonathan |title=Number of COVID-19 cases in Saskatchewan rises to 26, 8 confirmed |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6708930/coronavirus-saskstachewan-government-to-provide-update/ |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=Global News |publisher=Corus Entertainment |date=March 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321141136/https://globalnews.ca/news/6708930/coronavirus-saskstachewan-government-to-provide-update/ |archive-date=March 21, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nOn March 21, 18 new cases were reported,<ref name=\"cases321\">{{cite news |last1=Djuric |first1=Mickey |title=Coronavirus: Saskatchewan reports 18 new COVID-19 cases, province totals 44 |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6713523/coronavirus-saskatchewan-new-cases/ |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=Global News |publisher=Corus Entertainment |date=March 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322131901/https://globalnews.ca/news/6713523/coronavirus-saskatchewan-new-cases/ |archive-date=March 22, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> including 11 healthcare workers who attended a physicians' bonspiel at a curling club in [[Edmonton]] from March 11 to 14.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/11-sask-healthcare-workers-test-positive-for-covid-19-after-curling-bonspiel-in-alta-1.4862909|title=11 Sask. healthcare workers test positive for COVID-19 after curling bonspiel in Alta.|date=2020-03-21|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=March 23, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323063048/https://regina.ctvnews.ca/11-sask-healthcare-workers-test-positive-for-covid-19-after-curling-bonspiel-in-alta-1.4862909|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The index case was reported to be a physician from Saskatchewan who had contracted COVID-19 in Las Vegas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edmontonjournal.com/news/local-news/covid-19-saskatchewan-medical-association-head-tests-positive-believes-he-contracted-illness-at-edmonton-bonspiel/|title=COVID-19: Physicians at medical curling bonspiel asked to self-isolate after one of Saskatchewan's top docs tests positive|last=Short|first=Dylan|date=2020-03-20|website=Edmonton Journal|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/news/how-an-edmonton-curling-tournament-became-a-hotspot-for-the-covid-19-outbreak-in-canada|title=How an Edmonton curling tournament became a hotspot for the COVID-19 outbreak in Canada|last=Dawson|first=Tyler|date=2020-03-27|website=National Post|language=en-CA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref name=\"edmontonjournal_20200323\">{{cite news|last=Dawson|first=Tyler|url=https://edmontonjournal.com/news/at-least-11-alberta-medical-professionals-have-covid-19-after-attending-edmonton-curling-bonspiel/wcm/b164eb48-bf46-404f-8153-d3ae0fe78716/|title=At least 11 Alberta medical professionals have COVID-19 after attending Edmonton curling bonspiel|date=March 23, 2020|newspaper=Edmonton Journal|access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, 14 new cases were reported, and only one was still presumptive.<ref name=\"cases323\">{{cite news |last1=Guignard |first1=Jonathan |title=Coronavirus: Saskatchewan reports 14 new COVID-19 cases, bringing total to 66 |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6719062/coronavirus-saskatchewan-to-provide-update-on-covid-19-pandemic/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Global News |publisher=Corus Entertainment |date=March 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323231240/https://globalnews.ca/news/6719062/coronavirus-saskatchewan-to-provide-update-on-covid-19-pandemic/ |archive-date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 24, six new confirmed cases were reported, totalling 72 confirmed cases. This includes four cases thought to possibly be the result of community transmission, pending a full investigation.<ref name=\"cases324\">{{cite news |last1=Piller |first1=Thomas |title=Coronavirus: Saskatchewan reports 6 new COVID-19 cases, bringing total to 72 |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6726305/coronavirus-saskatchewan-covid-19-cases-march-24/ |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Global News |publisher=Corus Entertainment |date=March 24, 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325130857/https://globalnews.ca/news/6726305/coronavirus-saskatchewan-covid-19-cases-march-24/ |archive-date=March 25, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Another new 14 cases were announced on March 25. On March 26 and 27, 9 new cases were reported each.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6743122/covid-19-saskatchewan-coronavirus-march-27/|title=9 new coronavirus cases reported in Saskatchewan; PPE goes missing from health authority|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327232129/https://globalnews.ca/news/6743122/covid-19-saskatchewan-coronavirus-march-27/|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"cases326\">{{cite news |last1=Giles |first1=David |title=Coronavirus: 9 new COVID-19 cases reported in Saskatchewan, total rises to 95 |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6738102/coronavirus-covid-19-saskatchewan-march-26/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Global News |publisher=Corus Entertainment |date=March 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327034843/https://globalnews.ca/news/6738102/coronavirus-covid-19-saskatchewan-march-26/ |archive-date=March 27, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, Saskatchewan announced the largest single-day increase in cases, at 30. The spike, especially in northern and central Saskatchewan, was attributed to 18 cases involving attendees of a snowmobile rally in [[Christopher Lake]] on March 14.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6746486/saskatchewan-covid-19-cases-march-28/|title=Saskatchewan sees biggest jump in COVID-19 cases, 30 reported Saturday|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329022053/https://globalnews.ca/news/6746486/saskatchewan-covid-19-cases-march-28/|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/30-new-cases-of-covid-19-in-sask-6-people-in-hospital-1.4872587|title=30 new cases of COVID-19 in Sask., 6 people in hospital|last=|first=|date=2020-03-28|website=CTV News Regina|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329001244/https://regina.ctvnews.ca/30-new-cases-of-covid-19-in-sask-6-people-in-hospital-1.4872587|archive-date=March 29, 2020|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The [[Saskatchewan Health Authority]] (SHA) initially announced two positive cases (including a participant, and a server at an associated dinner) on March 25, and has advised self-isolation for anyone who had attended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://saskatoon.ctvnews.ca/two-people-who-attended-christopher-lake-snowmobile-rally-test-positive-for-covid-19-sha-1.4868716|title=Two people who attended Christopher Lake snowmobile rally test positive for COVID-19: SHA|last=|first=|date=2020-03-25|website=CTV News Saskatoon|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326165207/https://saskatoon.ctvnews.ca/two-people-who-attended-christopher-lake-snowmobile-rally-test-positive-for-covid-19-sha-1.4868716|archive-date=March 26, 2020|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/14-new-covid-19-cases-in-sask-as-province-limits-gatherings-to-10-people-1.4867855|title=14 new COVID-19 cases in Sask. as province limits gatherings to 10 people|date=2020-03-25|website=CTV News Regina|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326165208/https://regina.ctvnews.ca/14-new-covid-19-cases-in-sask-as-province-limits-gatherings-to-10-people-1.4867855|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, the confirmed case count rose to 176, and Saskatchewan also reported its first deaths from COVID-19. Both people were in their 70s and were from separate parts of the province.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatoon/coronavirus-saskatchewan-1.5514563 |title=COVID-19 in Sask: Province marks 'sad milestone' of first 2 deaths |last1=Quenneville |first1=Guy |last2=Hunter |first2=Adam |work=[[CBC News]] |date=2020-03-30 |access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nBy April 6, Saskatchewan had 253 cases and 81 recoveries. For the first time, the number of new recoveries (14) exceeded the number of new cases (4).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/4-new-covid-19-cases-in-sask-province-encourages-downloading-saskalert-app-1.4884205|title=4 new COVID-19 cases in Sask., province encourages downloading SaskAlert app|date=2020-04-06|website=CTV News Regina|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> On April 8, the SHA released its preliminary<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://thestarphoenix.com/news/local-news/saskatchewan-premier-plans-televised-address-before-releasing-reopening-plan/|title=Saskatchewan premier plans televised address before releasing reopening plan|date=2020-04-21|website=Saskatoon Star-Phoenix|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> modelling data, which had projected \"low\" and \"upper-range\" scenarios with between 153,000 to 408,000 cases respectively, and 3,075 to 8,370 deaths respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/saskatchewan-is-not-immune-health-authority-estimates-up-to-408k-covid-19-infections-1.4888076|title='Saskatchewan is not immune': Health authority estimates up to 408K COVID-19 infections|last=|first=|date=2020-04-08|website=CTV News Regina|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\nSeven new cases and recoveries were announced the next day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/saskatchewan-reaches-260-covid-19-cases-7-new-recoveries-1.4886679|title=Saskatchewan reaches 260 COVID-19 cases, 7 new recoveries|date=2020-04-07|website=CTV News Regina|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>  The total number of cases continued to rise, reaching 289 on April 11, though the remaining active cases fell to 138 \u2014 dropping for the first time below the number of recoveries (which rose to 147).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/sask-now-has-more-covid-19-recoveries-than-active-cases-1.4892399 |title=Sask. now has more COVID-19 recoveries than active cases |website=CTV News Regina |date=April 11, 2020 |access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, Saskatchewan reported 14 recoveries and two new cases (totalling 300).<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/2-new-covid-19-cases-in-sask-premier-starting-on-plan-to-re-open-province-1.4893631|title=2 new COVID-19 cases in Sask., premier starting on plan to 're-open' province|last=Hill|first=Katherine|date=2020-04-13|website=CTV News Regina|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6812934/coronavirus-saskatchewan-2-new-cases-14-recoveries/|title=2 new coronavirus cases, 14 more recoveries reported in Saskatchewan|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> The next day, only one new case was reported, and nine new recoveries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/1-new-covid-19-case-in-sask-9-new-recoveries-1.4895306|title=1 new COVID-19 case in Sask., 9 new recoveries|date=2020-04-14|website=CTV News Regina|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nOn April 17, Shahab announced that the province was monitoring cases tied to [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on long-term care facilities|long-term care facilities]], including an \"outbreak situation\" at one in [[La Loche]], a second staff member of one in Regina testing positive, and three residents of said home with symptoms (which later tested negative).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leaderpost.com/news/saskatchewan/three-regina-seniors-home-residents-with-covid-19-symptoms-test-negative-eden-care/|title=Three Regina seniors home residents with COVID-19 symptoms test negative: Eden Care|last=|first=|date=2020-04-20|website=Regina Leader-Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/residents-staff-test-positive-for-covid-19-at-care-homes-in-regina-northern-sask-1.4901216|title=Residents, staff test positive for COVID-19 at care homes in Regina, northern Sask.|last=Hill|first=Katherine|date=2020-04-17|website=CTV News Regina|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> On April 21, health officer for North Saskatchewan Rim Zayed stated that the cases in La Loche were \"under control\".<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatoon/covid-19-saskatchewan-april-21-2020-1.5539885|title=COVID-19 in Sask: New testing sites will help monitor impact of reopening plan|last=Bridges|first=Alica|date=2020-04-21|website=CBC News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> The SHA plans to release updated modelling.<ref name=\":15\" />\n\nOn April 23, Premier Moe gave a televised address (the first such address by the Premier of Saskatchewan since [[Roy Romanow]]'s tenure), announcing that the province had \"flattened the curve\", and that he and Shahab would unveil a five-stage process to \"gradually and methodically\" restore normal commerce and services. He explained that the province had to balance the risks of doing so too quickly (which could cause the virus to spread again), and doing so too slowly (which could cause \"permanent damage to the livelihoods of thousands of Saskatchewan people\"), and that the province was \"looking at ways to increase testing and contact tracing in the days ahead\".<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6855670/saskatchewan-reopen-coronavirus-scott-moe/|title=Saskatchewan to \u2018cautiously\u2019 reopen from the coronavirus pandemic in 5 phases|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/sask-premier-set-to-make-televised-address-ahead-of-plan-to-re-open-economy-1.4905939|title=Sask. premier set to make televised address ahead of plan to re-open economy|last=Hill|first=Katherine|date=2020-04-21|website=Regina|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref name=\":15\" /> Moe also stated that Saskatchewan was 70% below the national average of cases per-province, and hospitalizations and deaths were 90% below average.<ref name=\":16\" />\n\n{{Image frame\n |caption = COVID-19 Cases in Saskatchewan<ref name=saskcovid19 />\n |pos = top\n |align = center\n |border = no\n |content = {{Gallery layout\n  |content = {{gallery layout content\n   |content = {{Graph:Chart\n    |type = rect\n    |width = 550\n    |height = 250\n    |xAxisAngle = -45\n    |colors = SkyBlue, Tomato, Black\n    |y1Title = Recovered\n    |y2Title = New cases\n    |y3Title = Deaths\n    |yAxisTitle = Daily\n    |x = 12 Mar, 13 Mar, 14 Mar, 15 Mar, 16 Mar, 17 Mar, 18 Mar, 19 Mar, 20 Mar, 21 Mar, 22 Mar, 23 Mar, 24 Mar, 25 Mar, 26 Mar, 27 Mar, 28 Mar,